article.headline: Utah nearly blows double-digit lead
article.linkText: Jazz hold off Nets for fourth straight victory
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- DeShawn Stevenson was feeling better, at least for a couple of hours. After missing Sunday's practice with the flu, Stevenson started Monday night and had 18 points and five rebounds to help lead the Utah Jazz to an 91-84 win over the New Jersey Nets. Utah improved to 9-1 at home, although it was close after the Jazz allowed a 19-point second-half lead dwindle to three with less than a minute to play before sealing it with four straight free throws. "You've got to be concerned. They're a great team," said Stevenson, who recovered from two early air balls and finished 7-for-12 from the field and 4-for-4 from the line. "I've just got to give credit to everybody that came up and played hard and made free throws. I think that helped us out big at the end." New Jersey was coming off a 13-point loss the night before at Sacramento and never quite recovered from a sluggish start. Utah took advantage of the Nets' fatigue and finished with a 51-25 advantage in rebounds. Andrei Kirilenko also scored 18 and had 10 rebounds for the Jazz. Greg Ostertag, who was benched last Friday for arguing with coach Jerry Sloan, had 10 points and 10 rebounds, and Matt Harpring added 16 points and nine rebounds before fouling out in the fourth quarter. "I've always said. You look at teams that are competitive, they have to rebound," Sloan said. "Everybody got to be a part of it tonight." New Jersey rallied in the third quarter and could have forced overtime or maybe won, but could never take a lead. The Nets lost their third straight game, closing a 5-game road trip at 2-3. "We've just been struggling. It's about effort right now," said Richard Jefferson, who led New Jersey with 22 points. "We've run into some very big teams and we've got to make a much better effort. That's what it is right now." Jason Kidd added 15 points and Kenyon Martin 10 for New Jersey. Nets coach Byron Scott said rebounds were a much bigger difference than cold shooting. "It's something we have to figure out. Rebounding doesn't have a lot to do with skill and technique. It has to do with your will against his will," Scott said. Utah was pulling away in the third quarter and appeared to have the game almost wrapped up before New Jersey started hitting some shots. The Nets trimmed a 19-point lead to 66-56 at the end of the third quarter with an 11-2 run, then continued to chip away in the fourth. Jefferson made two free throws and then a layup with just under than 5 minutes remaining to cut the lead to 77-73, and the Nets kept it close from there. Jefferson cut it to 87-84 on a 3-pointer with about 35 seconds to go, but that was the last gasp for the Nets. Raul Lopez drew a foul and went 2-for-2 from the line, then after Kidd missed a 20-footer, the rebound kicked out to Raja Bell who was fouled and made both free throws to seal it. "We let them stay around and we need to get better at keeping teams down," Bell said.

Game notes
Twins Jarron and Jason Collins were on the court at the same time briefly in the third quarter. Jason won the family scoring title with eight points for the Nets. Jarron scored three for Utah. ... The Nets came out flat, going 1-for-7 in the first 5:12 as the Jazz opened with a 13-2 lead ... Utah had just two free throws in the first half. ... The BYU drum line performed at halftime and drew more boos than cheers from the apparently pro-University of Utah crowd.
